The key ideals mentioned in the Preamble of the Constitution of India are:

1. To constitute India into a "SOVEREIGN SOCIALIST SECULAR DEMOCRATIC REPUBLIC."
2. To secure to all its citizens:
   - "JUSTICE," which includes social, economic, and political justice;
   - "LIBERTY" of thought, expression, belief, faith, and worship;
   - "EQUALITY" of status and of opportunity;
3. To promote among all citizens "FRATERNITY" assuring the dignity of the individual and the "unity and integrity of the Nation."

These ideals collectively express the fundamental values and objectives that the Constitution aims to achieve for the nation and its people.

Parliament can alter the boundaries, area, or name of an existing State under **Article 3** of the Constitution of India. Article 3 empowers Parliament by law to:

(a) form a new State by separation of territory from any State or by uniting two or more States or parts of States or by uniting any territory to a part of any State;

(b) increase the area of any State;

(c) diminish the area of any State;

(d) alter the boundaries of any State;

(e) alter the name of any State.

However, no Bill for this purpose shall be introduced in either House of Parliament except on the recommendation of the President. Further, if the Bill affects the area, boundaries, or name of any State, the President must refer the Bill to the Legislature of that State for expressing its views within a specified period or any further period allowed by the President, and that period must have expired before introduction of the Bill.

In this Article, "State" includes a Union territory in clauses (a) to (e), but in the proviso regarding the Bill's introduction and reference to the State Legislature, "State" does not include a Union territory.

Thus, the power conferred on Parliament by Article 3 includes the power to form a new State or Union territory by uniting a part of any State or Union territory to any other State or Union territory.

This is the constitutional provision under which Parliament can alter the boundaries, area, or name of an existing State.

Reimbursement for expenses not related to hospitalization is generally not covered. The policy specifically covers pre-hospitalisation and post-hospitalisation medical expenses only if:

(i) A claim for In-patient Hospitalisation has been accepted under the relevant clauses;

(ii) The pre- or post-hospitalisation medical expenses are related to the same Illness or Injury for which the hospitalization claim was accepted;

(iii) The expenses fall within the specified number of days and amount limits as per the Policy Schedule or Certificate of Insurance.

Expenses unrelated to hospitalization or not connected to the illness or injury for which hospitalization was claimed are excluded. Additionally, non-medical expenses such as convenience items for personal comfort, ambulatory devices, and medical equipment used at home (except when part of room expenses) are not reimbursable. Routine health check-ups, medical certificates, vaccinations (except when part of hospitalization or daycare treatment), and treatments unrelated to hospitalization are also excluded from reimbursement.

Therefore, reimbursement is limited to medical expenses directly related to hospitalization and its immediate pre- and post-hospitalisation periods, and expenses not related to hospitalization are not eligible for reimbursement under this policy.
